HEADWORD: Hoarse
<hw>Hoarse</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Hoarser</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Hoarsest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>hors</ets>, also
<ets>hos</ets>, <ets>has</ets>, AS. <ets>h⟦amac⟧s</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>heesch</ets>, G. <ets>heiser</ets>, Icel. <ets>h⟦amac⟧ss</ets>,
Dan. <ets>h⟦ae⟧s</ets>, Sw. <ets>hes</ets>. Cf. Prov. E.
<ets>heazy</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having a harsh, rough, grating
voice or sound, as when affected with a cold; making a rough, harsh cry
or sound; <as>as, the <ex>hoarse</ex> raven</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>hoarse</qex> resounding shore.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Harsh; grating; discordant; -- said of any
sound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hoarsely</ent>⟦br⟧
